	abstract = {Introduction: Glioma is a common brain tumor. It can impair various cognitive functions such as social cognition. Prosody, a component of social cognition, remains little studied in glioma patients. Aim: The main aim of the study is to identify any impairment in the recognition of linguistic and/or emotional prosody in patients with glioma, before and after surgery. Materials and methods: 23 patients with glioma were evaluated preoperatively and 19 postoperatively. Different tasks were used to test recognition of linguistic and emotional prosody (i-MEL, Reverse Correlation, Pseudophrases).
Results: Deficits in prosody recognition are diagnosed as early as the preoperative assessment, with greater impairment of linguistic prosody than emotional prosody. After surgery, a decline in performance is revealed. Finally, only for linguistic prosody, the postoperative drop in performance is greater in patients with a right-hemisphere lesion. For all these results, inter-individual variability is noted. Discussion: These data are relatively innovative, as few studies have looked at prosody in glioma patients. Among studies of brain-injured patients, aprosodia is regularly found. More research is needed in this area to further explore the mechanisms underlying prosodic alterations.
Conclusion: This study highlights the clinical and fundamental importance of studying prosody in patients. Indeed, they appear to present prosody recognition disorders preoperatively, with a decline in performance postoperatively.},
